Yes — you can keep a single ArgoCD application. The trick is to make that one application **multi-source**: one source renders your datastore manifests, another pulls the Helm chart, and a third provides the values file. ArgoCD reconciles all of them under one Application with one sync and one health view.

Your current Langfuse app is already a Helm source (plus the `$values` ref). You just **add a third source** for the Postgres/ClickHouse/Valkey manifests and drop the idea of a separate infra app:

```yaml
apiVersion: argoproj.io/v1alpha1
kind: Application
metadata:
  name: langfuse-stg
  namespace: argocd
spec:
  project: default
  destination:
    server: https://kubernetes.default.svc
    namespace: aidata
  sources:
    # 1) your in-cluster datastores (Postgres + ClickHouse + Valkey)
    - repoURL: https://git.example.com/infra/gitops.git
      targetRevision: STG
      path: apps/langfuse/overlays/stg

    # 2) the Langfuse Helm chart, fed the values file from source #3
    - repoURL: https://langfuse.github.io/langfuse-k8s
      chart: langfuse
      targetRevision: 1.5.34
      helm:
        valueFiles:
          - $values/apps/langfuse/values/values-stg.yaml

    # 3) value-file provider (ref only — renders nothing on its own)
    - repoURL: https://git.example.com/infra/gitops.git
      targetRevision: STG
      ref: values
  syncPolicy:
    automated: { prune: true, selfHeal: true }
    syncOptions: [CreateNamespace=true]
```

To get apply-ordering inside the single app, add a sync-wave annotation to your three datastore manifests so they go first:

```yaml
metadata:
  annotations:
    argocd.argoproj.io/sync-wave: "-1"   # datastores before the chart (wave 0)
```

A few things to know:
- **Needs ArgoCD ≥ 2.6** — that's when multiple `sources` and the `$values` ref pattern landed. On older versions you'd have to split into two apps.
- **Ordering isn't strict, and that's okay.** ArgoCD/Helm won't block until the databases are *ready*; the sync-wave just controls apply order. If langfuse-web/worker start before the DB is reachable, they crashloop-retry and recover once it's up (`selfHeal` helps). The wave annotation just makes it tidy.
- This **replaces** both your current app and the would-be infra app — you end with exactly **one** Application, just multi-source.

If you'd rather not touch the Application at all, the alternative is inlining the datastore manifests into the chart's `extraManifests: []` value — also one app, but you'd be pasting full StatefulSets into your values file, which is messier than keeping them as their own source. I'd go with the multi-source approach above.